    <h2 id="what-is-detox">What Detox Gummies Actually Do (and What They Do Not)</h2>

    <p>The supplement industry's use of "detox" is one of the most misleading marketing terms in health and wellness. Your liver processes and neutralizes toxins through a sophisticated two-phase enzymatic system involving cytochrome P450 enzymes (Phase I) and conjugation reactions (Phase II). Your kidneys filter blood, removing waste products through urine. These systems operate continuously and do not require supplemental activation.</p>

    <p>What legitimate detox supplements can do is support these existing systems. Milk thistle (silymarin) has demonstrated hepatoprotective effects in over 100 clinical studies, protecting liver cells from damage caused by alcohol, medications, and environmental toxins. Apple cider vinegar's acetic acid content supports digestive function and may improve insulin sensitivity. Fiber binds to bile acids and supports elimination of metabolic waste through regular bowel movements. These are genuine, evidence-based benefits — distinct from the fantastical "cleansing" claims that pervade detox marketing.</p>

